# RDP Brute Force Attack

## Overview
In this scenario, I simulated a brute-force attack against a Windows 10 machine using the Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP). The goal was to generate authentication failures and observe how they appear in Wazuh.

## Environment
- Attacker: Kali Linux (10.10.10.10)
- Target: Windows 10 (10.10.10.30)

## Attack Execution
I used Hydra with a common password list to attempt multiple logins:

hydra -l test -P rockyou.txt rdp://10.10.10.30

This generated a high number of failed login attempts in a short period of time.

## Detection in Wazuh
Relevant logs:
- Event ID 4625 – Failed logon attempts

Filtering example:
win.system.eventID: 4625

## Analysis
The pattern was very clear:
- repeated login failures
- same source IP
- short time interval

This is a typical brute-force signature.

## MITRE ATT&CK
T1110 – Brute Force

## Takeaway
Even a simple attack like this creates a strong signal in authentication logs. Easy win for detection if logging is enabled.
